    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3488458078" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3488458078" />
    <a title="Brogan Lane&amp;#x1f4d6;" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28434314-brogan-lane-x1f4d6"><img alt="Brogan Lane&amp;#x1f4d6;" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1615823289p2/28434314.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3488458078?book_show_action=true">Oct 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brogan Lane&amp;#x1f4d6;" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brogan Lane&amp;#x1f4d6;" href="/user/show/28434314-brogan-lane-x1f4d6">Brogan Lane&amp;#x1f4d6;</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/28434314-brogan-lane-x1f4d6?shelf=2020">2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3488458078&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3488458078" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17801262347326232158">With short stories anthologies, there&apos;s always the risk of liking a few and not all of them, and that&apos;s what happened here with <i>Vampires Never Get Old</i>. I was so excited about this release: vampires! Yes! Vampires making a comeback, finally! I was here for it, but I&apos;m severely disappointed at the result.<br/><br/><b>SEVEN NIGHTS FOR DYING</b> by Tessa Gratton<br/><br/>⭐️⭐️⭐️<br/><br/><i>“Most don’t live past the first year, but those who do are nearly always young women. You need to live, I think, because of what’s been denied you. You</i></span>
  <span id="freeText17801262347326232158" style="display:none">With short stories anthologies, there's always the risk of liking a few and not all of them, and that's what happened here with <i>Vampires Never Get Old</i>. I was so excited about this release: vampires! Yes! Vampires making a comeback, finally! I was here for it, but I'm severely disappointed at the result.<br /><br /><b>SEVEN NIGHTS FOR DYING</b> by Tessa Gratton<br /><br />⭐️⭐️⭐️<br /><br /><i>“Most don’t live past the first year, but those who do are nearly always young women. You need to live, I think, because of what’s been denied you. You’re already hungry, every young I’ve ever met has been hungry – that makes the transition easier. You know how to live with hunger. And anger – Seti is right about that. Not just any anger, not old masculine anger, sharpened with toxicity, but true anger, the kind that fills you up like a light.”</i><br /><br />In a lot of vampire stories, the choice to become a vampire is either a die-or-turn situation and never a real choice, never contemplated and thought on. Seven Nights For Dying is centred around the heroine’s right to choose to become a vampire over a seven-day period. She weighs the pros and cons, wonders whether she’ll be remembered by her friend and whether turning into a vampire will erase the grief she feels over her mother’s death. I enjoyed this one.<br /><br /><b>THE BOYS FROM BLOOD RIVER</b> by Rebecca Roanhorse<br /><br />⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️<br /><br /><i>“It’s just a song, Lukas. Nobody believes the Blood River Boys will actually appear if you sing it.”</i><br /><br />This story gave me really strong Lost Boys vibes, and I loved how Roanhorse was able to create a small-town legend within just the first few pages out of twenty-five and make it spooky. This story follows a gay, Native American named Lukas, and his life is shit – his mother is sick, he doesn’t have other family or friends to help him, and he experiences racism and extreme, violent bullying from three white shitheads. He’s alone and the only thing that he hopes for is that the Blood River Boys would come to town and take him from it all. I really liked this one because from the moment the Boys appeared, Roanhorse made sure we knew they were dangerous.<br /><br /><b>SENIOR YEAR SUCKS</b> by Julie Murphy<br /><br />⭐️⭐️<br /><br /><i>“It’s not like I woke up one day and decided to become a vampire. My humanity was violently stolen from me. I’m continuing on, the only way I know how.”</i><br /><br />I liked the concept of this one: of a vampire slayer and a vampire in close proximity, almost forced to speak to one another rather than give in to their instincts to kill one another. But there was an insane amount of info-dumping at the beginning that didn’t really work as it was a short story. It would’ve worked better if it has started with Jolene and Alma meeting and the reader finding out who they were that way. There were a lot of Buffy references as Jolene was not only a vampire slayer but also a cheerleader. It felt…underwhelming.<br /><br />It shocked me that this is the same author who wrote Dumplin’! <br /><br /><b>THE BOY AND THE BELL</b> by Heidi Heilig<br /><br />⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️<br /><br /><i>“The century is ending, and with it, old ways of thinking. Of being. In the clear and steady gleam of electric lights, superstition turns to foolishness; in the crucible of the combustion engine, false beliefs are burned away. And under the scalpel and the microscope, the human form is revealed to be much closer to animals’ than to angels’. In the secret spaces, man has discovered cells, not souls. Death has become final; there is no such thing as eternal life. As a metaphor, live burial is much more relatable than the story of the vampire.”</i><br /><br />YESSSS! This story was amazing. Heidi Heilig takes the burial traditions of the superstitious and turns it into a very spooky tale. This follows Will, an aspiring doctor who, to make money, is a body snatcher for a university. On one particular night, he answers a bell ringing at the grave of an aristocratic boy named Maxwell. Upon un-burying him, Will discovers that Maxwell is not alive after all, but a hungry vampire. This is set around the release of Bram Stoker’s Dracula, and Will uses it, almost as a guide, to quickly distinguish what Maxwell is and how to deal with him. Heilig creates such a spooky atmosphere in a cemetery at night and achieves to craft Will’s character so well in such few pages. Will is trans, and without info-dumping, Heilig cleverly includes Will’s past, his feelings and thoughts on his own body. I loved this one a lot. It had a very satisfying ending.<br /><br /><b>A GUIDEBOOK FOR THE NEWLY SIRED DESI VAMPIRE</b> by Samira Ahmed<br /><br />⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️<br /><br /><i>“You’re also probably panicking because you stayed out way past your curfew and your ummi is going to kill you. Good news: technically, you’re already dead! This may well undermine the ferocity of your mother’s threats. (Hahaha that’s a joke – it’s not like something as banal as death could spare you from her wrath for breaking curfew. Please.).”</i><br /><br />This was SO cool! Unlike the ones previous, this is formatted as like an online guide to new baby desi vampires. The vampires in vampire literature are predominantly white, male and European: Samira Ahmed introduces us to the possible experiences a desi vampire may encounter. Vampersand is here to help. It offers advice on a newly turned vampire’s mental health, most popular questions asked, coming to terms with who they are now, their cuisine, advice on their love life and match matching as a vampire and what their future looks like. I feel like if vampirism was real, this would be the reality. Other vampires helping newly turned vampires out. This was hilarious and thought-provoking, especially as Ahmed mentioned colonialization, the British Empire, and how it was the fault of white vampire tourists that the vampire population has risen. This was so intriguing!<br /><br /><b>IN KIND</b> by Kayla Whaley<br /><br />⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️<br /><br /><i>“My heart doesn’t beat anymore, but I can feel its presence, a great hunk of meat behind a cage of bone. How will I know when I’m scared or excited if my heart can’t skip a beat?”</i><br /><br />This story was really something – I loved it! In the afterword by Zoraida Cordova and Natalie C. Parker, they say: “Grace is transformed into a vampire, and while she receives some of those enhanced magical senses, her body remains her body. Being yourself, even undead, is pretty powerful.” Our MC Grace Williams has been wheel-chair bound since birth, and this story starts off when her father attempts to murder her because he found the role of caregiver too much. Not only did this comment on how vampirism has been used over and over as a ‘magical cure’ and is an erasure of disability, but also societal views on disability. The news deemed Grace’s murder a ‘mercy-killing’ because of her disability, when in fact, it was cold-blooded murder and sympathised more with Grace’s father than Grace herself, who had no say in what happened to her. Grace was saved by a vampire, Seanan, but not saved from her disability, from death. I really loved this story. It had a very satisfying ending!!<br /><br /><b>VAMPIRES NEVER SAY DIE</b> by Zoraida Cordova and Natalie C. Parker<br /><br />⭐️<br /><br /><i>“Not everyone I bite becomes like me. I have to choose. I get to choose. And over the years, I have chosen women like me. Women who were told they were less than, unworthy, weak. Women who were hungry for the world. Women with fangs. My petits crocs.”</i><br /><br />If this story had been solely focused on Brittany as a two-hundred-year-old vampire, I think I would’ve liked it better. It had insane Twilight vibes as Brittany is an old vampire speaking to Theolinda since she was fifteen over Instagram, and I didn’t like it. It was kinda creepy. Theolinda has organised a birthday party for Brittany – even though they’ve never met in person – and somehow manages to invite all of Brittany’s vampire group. Her fast realisation that she’s surrounded by vampires felt really anti-climactic and even when Brittany stormed in, their meeting was just meh. It was ruined by – of all things – a candelabra falling on Theolinda and piercing her neck, and her begging Brittany to turn her into a vampire. Hmmmmm…no. It was all very rushed and unsatisfying.<br /><br /><b>BESTIARY</b> by Laura Ruby<br /><br />⭐️<br /><br /><i>“Jude had offered herself to the golden boy she loved and, in turn, he’d offered her to some magical beasts he loved more. She was meant to be the toy, but she’d become something else. Something with claws, something with teeth, blah blah blag. A different kind of beast. She’d taken the first bites, but she’d let Olive and Nell do the rest.”</i><br /><br />Hmmmm…what the heck was this?? This was supposed to explore the connection between animals and the supernatural, but I got none of that. Jude might as well have not been a vampire because she was more a psychic who could read animals’ minds at the zoo she worked at. Not for me.<br /><br /><b>MIRRORS, WINDOWS &amp; SELFIES</b> by Mark Oshiro<br /><br />⭐️⭐️<br /><br /><i>“I grabbed the mirror and held it up to my face as my parents’ screams filled the desert air. There I was. Cisco. Me.”</i><br /><br />Cisco is a vampire, but not your average vampire. He was born a vampire, and because of this, his parents, also vampires, hide away from other vampires out of fear of what they could do to Cisco. The format of this story is multiple blog posts made Cisco under the pseudonym: invisibleb0y, where he writes about his isolated, lonely life. I liked the format and liked it even more when comments were featured written by humans who think Cisco is telling a fictional story for views. But I think the plot itself was too big and complex for such a short piece. This could very well be a full-length novel, and Mark Oshiro squishing that down to 36 pages resulted in quite a rushed underdeveloped story. I wanted more.<br /><br /><b>THE HOUSE OF BLACK SAPPHIRES</b> by Dhonielle Clayton<br /><br />⭐️⭐️<br /><br /><i>“They said the Turner women of the House of Black Sapphires were a little strange. That they were just too beautiful. That they were up to no good. They said the Turner women were vampires. And whenever that word appeared, it was time to go.”</i><br /><br />I liked the concept of Eternal women, but I don’t understand why they couldn’t just be vampires? If this wasn’t in an anthology specifically about vampires, I would’ve thought they were witches as each daughter has an individual ‘power’ or ‘skill. Which we didn’t actually get to see any of them display. This story follows the Turner family, made up of Eternal women and their father, who move to New Orleans, and there they have to integrate themselves back into the magical society the mother left so long ago. The beginning was exceptional and I really loved Dhonielle’s writing – but I feel like this was too much of an idea for a short story. The ending was abrupt and it felt like, when I turned the page, there would be another chapter. A lot of questions were asked by our MC Bea, but none of them were answered. <br /><br /><b>FIRST KILL</b> by V. E. Schwab<br /><br />⭐️⭐️<br /><br /><i>“Calliope’s mouth pulls into a crooked grin. And Jules stares back, smiles back, and thinks – Let the hunt begin.”</i><br /><br />So surprised that I didn’t like this as much as I wanted to. I bought this anthology for two reasons: vampires and V.E. Schwab – and I found myself just not really liking this. I think I made the mistake of thinking this book wasn’t YA, but a large number of short stories in this is based around teenagers and school and this was too. I thought V.E. Schwab would’ve come up with something a little more. This follows Juliette a vampire and Calliope a girl she has a crush on – who turns out to come from a family of monster hunters. Again, I think this idea is too big for a short story because the ending was a major cliff-hanger, and I felt unsatisfied with the whole thing. The title was a good choice as both characters were planning on making their first kill, but what was supposed to be the climax just flopped for me.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17801262347326232158" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


